      <chapter id="512">
        <pagenum>6</pagenum>
        <subchapter>0</subchapter>
        <title>Post-Viewing Questions</title>
        <content>&lt;p style="text-align: left;"&gt;&lt;span style="font-family: arial,helvetica,sans-serif; font-size: small;"&gt;As you saw in Johanna’s classroom vignette in the PowerPoint presentation, teachers frequently try to tackle attendance issues on their own. They often end up feeling alone in their efforts to improve learner persistence. If it “takes a village” to educate a child, it takes a whole adult education program to promote learner persistence!&lt;b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ol&gt;
&lt;li style="text-align: left;"&gt;&lt;span style="font-family: arial,helvetica,sans-serif; font-size: small;"&gt;Which of the strategies shared by subject matter experts Rob Jenkins and Maricel Santos in the PowerPoint presentation stand out for you? Which would you most like to try? (Jot down your ideas in your course &lt;a target="_blank" href="$@JOURNALVIEWBYID*4993@$"&gt;journal&lt;/a&gt; or in the &lt;a title="LINKS COP Discussion" href="https://community.lincs.ed.gov/comment/12214#comment-12214%20" target="_blank"&gt;LINCS Community of Practice discussion&lt;/a&gt;).&lt;/span&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li style="text-align: left;"&gt;&lt;span style="line-height: 1.231; font-family: arial,helvetica,sans-serif; font-size: small;"&gt;&lt;span style="line-height: 1.231;"&gt;In what ways have teachers in your program worked together to boost learner motivation and persistence? (Use the "Motivating Adult Learners to Persist" &lt;a title="Post-Viewing Questions" href="https://community.lincs.ed.gov/comment/12214#comment-12214" target="_blank"&gt;course discussion thread&lt;/a&gt; in the LINCS Evidence-Based Professional Development Community of Practice, to share your ideas with other practitioners and see what other course participants have said).&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;
