        <title>The Strategies at Work: Observing Alternative Assessment of Discussion Skills </title>
        <content>&lt;p style="text-align: left;"&gt;&lt;span style="font-family: arial,helvetica,sans-serif; font-size: small;"&gt;One way that students build skills is by watching how others learn and by listening to how their peers think. In this video assignment, you will observe a group of young adult learners engage in a peer feedback activity.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h4 style="text-align: left;"&gt;&lt;span style="font-family: arial,helvetica,sans-serif; font-size: small;"&gt;Pre-Viewing Questions:&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/h4&gt;
&lt;p style="text-align: left; margin-left: 30px;"&gt;&lt;span style="font-family: arial,helvetica,sans-serif; font-size: xx-small;"&gt; &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style="text-align: left; margin-left: 30px;"&gt;&lt;span style="font-family: arial,helvetica,sans-serif; font-size: small;"&gt;Before you watch this video on Alternative Assessment, reflect on your current teaching practice and/or jot down in your &lt;a target="_blank" href="$@JOURNALVIEWBYID*4993@$"&gt;journal&lt;/a&gt; your answers to the following questions, or use &lt;a title="Motivating Adult Learners Course Discussion Thread" href="https://community.lincs.ed.gov/discussion/motivating-adult-learners-persist-online-course#comment-12215" target="_blank"&gt;the course thread in the LINCS Evidence-Based Professional Development Community of Practice&lt;/a&gt; to share your ideas with other practitioners and also see what previous course participants have said.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ol&gt;
&lt;li style="margin-left: 30px;"&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-family: arial,helvetica,sans-serif; font-size: small;"&gt;Do you have techniques that you use to help students deal with their errors so they do not undercut their motivation? What are they? &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li style="margin-left: 30px;"&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-family: arial,helvetica,sans-serif; font-size: small;"&gt;Have you used peer feedback activities in your teaching? What are the strengths and challenges of using that approach? &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;
&lt;h4 style="text-align: left;"&gt;&lt;span style="font-family: arial,helvetica,sans-serif; font-size: small;"&gt;While-Viewing questions:&lt;b&gt; &lt;/b&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/h4&gt;
&lt;p style="text-align: left; margin-left: 30px;"&gt;&lt;span style="font-family: arial,helvetica,sans-serif; font-size: xx-small;"&gt; &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style="text-align: left; margin-left: 30px;"&gt;&lt;span style="font-family: arial,helvetica,sans-serif; font-size: small;"&gt;As you watch the video, keep the following guiding questions in mind:&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ol&gt;
&lt;li style="margin-left: 30px;"&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-family: arial,helvetica,sans-serif; font-size: small;"&gt;What is the level of engagement demonstrated by the students as they conduct the activity? &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li style="margin-left: 30px;"&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-family: arial,helvetica,sans-serif; font-size: small;"&gt;What are some of the benefits that the students describe in their individual reports?&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;
